00:49:38.900 --> 00:49:42.140
and creating a petition and
saying this is unacceptable.

00:49:42.140 --> 00:49:46.310
You have to continue to be that
person who's going to advocate.

00:49:46.310 --> 00:49:48.500
It doesn't require
100 people to do it,

00:49:48.500 --> 00:49:50.780
but if two or three
people consistently do it,

00:49:50.780 --> 00:49:53.270
someone is going to have to
say, there are people watching,

00:49:53.270 --> 00:49:55.790
and we need to pay attention
to what's going on.

00:49:55.790 --> 00:49:58.550
AUDIENCE: My question is,
with all the statistics

00:49:58.550 --> 00:50:01.100
that you laid out
for Brownsville,

00:50:01.100 --> 00:50:06.890
how do you justify or explain
teachers who have little

00:50:06.890 --> 00:50:11.240
to no experience coming
into these communities

00:50:11.240 --> 00:50:16.760
where 60-some-odd percent
have learning challenges

00:50:16.760 --> 00:50:18.830
that a teacher with
little to no experience

00:50:18.830 --> 00:50:21.050
wouldn't have been
exposed to, let

00:50:21.050 --> 00:50:24.050
alone the cultural
differences and just all

00:50:24.050 --> 00:50:26.210
of those challenges
that go into it?

00:50:26.210 --> 00:50:27.950
From my point of
view, I feel like you

00:50:27.950 --> 00:50:31.340
need experience and, sort
of, to be wet behind the ears

00:50:31.340 --> 00:50:37.040
before you can identify that
maybe a child is being abused

00:50:37.040 --> 00:50:44.000
in some way, or see some sort
of mental or learning challenge.

00:50:44.000 --> 00:50:46.910
And some of that, no matter how
much school experience you get,

00:50:46.910 --> 00:50:49.220
you only get from experience.

00:50:49.220 --> 00:50:52.340
NADIA LOPEZ: So
couple of things--

00:50:52.340 --> 00:50:54.920
veteran teachers are expensive.

00:50:54.920 --> 00:50:59.720
So I would love to have a
gang load of veteran teachers,

00:50:59.720 --> 00:51:02.750
but what they make,
their average,

00:51:02.750 --> 00:51:04.370
would eat up my budget.

00:51:04.370 --> 00:51:08.570
So when I'm a
smaller school, when

00:51:08.570 --> 00:51:12.440
I'm in a position where I have
to rationalize or ration off

00:51:12.440 --> 00:51:16.970
the money, I sit and I say,
how much money do I have.

00:51:16.970 --> 00:51:21.140
One veteran teacher could
be the cost of two teachers,

00:51:21.140 --> 00:51:23.390
because that's how much
they stand to make.

00:51:23.390 --> 00:51:26.520
A veteran teacher-- for
some of them, it's $75,000.

00:51:26.520 --> 00:51:29.360
For others, it's $125,000.

00:51:29.360 --> 00:51:31.610
They range.

00:51:31.610 --> 00:51:35.060
So I can't afford to have
as many veteran teachers

00:51:35.060 --> 00:51:36.680
in the building.

00:51:36.680 --> 00:51:37.760
That's one.

00:51:37.760 --> 00:51:39.770
The second thing
that becomes an issue

00:51:39.770 --> 00:51:44.510
is, people don't want
to work in those areas

00:51:44.510 --> 00:51:46.310
because it's a challenge.

00:51:46.310 --> 00:51:48.920
It requires a lot of energy.

00:51:48.920 --> 00:51:51.560
If you are a parent yourself
and you have a child,

00:51:51.560 --> 00:51:56.450
your thought process is, can I
sacrifice the time and energy

00:51:56.450 --> 00:51:58.880
that's required to
do this, that's going

00:51:58.880 --> 00:52:00.680
to take away from my child?

00:52:00.680 --> 00:52:05.100
And that's something people
have to ask for themselves.

00:52:05.100 --> 00:52:07.460
The other thing is, you have
a lot of teaching programs

00:52:07.460 --> 00:52:10.526
that are targeted
to giving us what's

00:52:10.526 --> 00:52:11.900
considered the
best and brightest

00:52:11.900 --> 00:52:13.500
to go into these spaces.

00:52:13.500 --> 00:52:15.446
But what they're learning
in the schools that

00:52:15.446 --> 00:52:16.820
are supposed to
be preparing them

00:52:16.820 --> 00:52:18.278
has nothing to do
with what they're

00:52:18.278 --> 00:52:21.590
going to face in the schools
that they're going to.

00:52:21.590 --> 00:52:24.440
So I have taken on
the daunting task

00:52:24.440 --> 00:52:28.880
of bringing in those
teaching prep programs

00:52:28.880 --> 00:52:32.420
and having those candidates
come and train at my school,

00:52:32.420 --> 00:52:34.884
because I really need them
to understand what's going

00:52:34.884 --> 00:52:36.050
to happen when they walk in.

00:52:36.050 --> 00:52:38.990
And I'm always in the
classrooms, always supporting,

00:52:38.990 --> 00:52:42.240
but I know what it's like,
because I was a teaching

00:52:42.240 --> 00:52:43.080
fellow.

00:52:43.080 --> 00:52:45.030
My first year, I
was not prepared.

00:52:45.030 --> 00:52:46.980
In my first year, for
the first three months,

00:52:46.980 --> 00:52:49.560
I cried every day like, I
want to go back to corporate.

00:52:49.560 --> 00:52:51.210
Why did I do this?

00:52:51.210 --> 00:52:52.680
Even though I'm
from Brooklyn, even

00:52:52.680 --> 00:52:54.971
though I was born and raised
around folks who were poor

00:52:54.971 --> 00:52:57.780
and we were struggling,
being in a classroom

00:52:57.780 --> 00:53:00.310
is a different dynamic.

00:53:00.310 --> 00:53:02.746
What sustained me was my faith.

00:53:02.746 --> 00:53:04.120
What sustained me
was that I knew

00:53:04.120 --> 00:53:06.550
someone had done it for me.

00:53:06.550 --> 00:53:09.680
And I had a child, so I
was going to figure it out.

00:53:09.680 --> 00:53:11.740
And what I saw was an injustice.

00:53:11.740 --> 00:53:13.930
Everyone is not built that way.

00:53:13.930 --> 00:53:19.450
So part of it is, no one is
asking the principals what

00:53:19.450 --> 00:53:20.860
the challenge is.

00:53:20.860 --> 00:53:23.890
They keep giving us
whatever they give us.

00:53:23.890 --> 00:53:25.690
People who keep
showing up are the ones

00:53:25.690 --> 00:53:29.830
who aren't the veteran
teachers, and so we're, kind of,

00:53:29.830 --> 00:53:34.480
called to task to make things
work in a short amount of time.

00:53:34.480 --> 00:53:36.220
Because when you
think about it, kids

00:53:36.220 --> 00:53:39.500
are only in school for
30 weeks out of the year.

00:53:39.500 --> 00:53:41.440
So it's systemic.

00:53:41.440 --> 00:53:45.160
It's not going to
be fixed overnight.

00:53:45.160 --> 00:53:46.540
But because of
people like me who

00:53:46.540 --> 00:53:49.650
are in the system, who are,
like, oh, this person--

00:53:49.650 --> 00:53:53.050
we've got to fix this and
we've got to work with them--

00:53:53.050 --> 00:53:56.110
it helps, but there's
not enough of me.

00:53:56.110 --> 00:53:57.580
There are really
great principals

00:53:57.580 --> 00:54:00.160
who are trying to do it,
but there's not enough.

00:54:00.160 --> 00:54:02.191
Because at the end of
the day, it's like,

00:54:02.191 --> 00:54:03.940
you have so much on
your plate that you're

00:54:03.940 --> 00:54:08.300
trying to get through, that
that just doesn't become

00:54:08.300 --> 00:54:11.364
a fight that you have anymore.

00:54:11.364 --> 00:54:12.270
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:54:12.270 --> 00:54:15.719
NADIA LOPEZ: You're welcome

00:54:15.719 --> 00:54:17.510
AUDIENCE: Hey, I just
had a quick question.

00:54:17.510 --> 00:54:20.720
You mentioned you kept your
school open till 9:00 or 10:00

00:54:20.720 --> 00:54:23.210
at night sometimes.

00:54:23.210 --> 00:54:25.760
So my kids after school,
they do the basketball.

00:54:25.760 --> 00:54:27.410
They got lots of
dads to coach that.

00:54:27.410 --> 00:54:29.150
I ran a computer
club for my kids--

00:54:29.150 --> 00:54:30.560
all that kind of stuff.

00:54:30.560 --> 00:54:32.780
What do your kids do
at the school for--

00:54:32.780 --> 00:54:36.140
I'm guessing-- like,
five hours afterwards?

00:54:36.140 --> 00:54:38.545
NADIA LOPEZ: They're
getting tutorial services.

00:54:38.545 --> 00:54:41.850
They're doing culinary arts.

00:54:41.850 --> 00:54:43.310
They're doing basketball.

00:54:43.310 --> 00:54:49.028
They're doing softball,
track, double dutch step,

00:54:49.028 --> 00:54:51.200
and clothing design.

00:54:51.200 --> 00:54:52.370
We have a program.

00:54:52.370 --> 00:54:53.890
So it's not them
just hanging out.

00:54:53.890 --> 00:54:56.330
It's actually a
structured program

00:54:56.330 --> 00:55:01.610
through SONYC, which
is what the mayor put

00:55:01.610 --> 00:55:04.740
as part of his initiative
for at-risk middle schools.

00:55:04.740 --> 00:55:08.450
We have funding in place,
where they pay them directly,

00:55:08.450 --> 00:55:09.494
to have these programs.

00:55:09.494 --> 00:55:10.910
But if I didn't
have that, there's

00:55:10.910 --> 00:55:15.130
also a BEACON program that
stays until 9:00 at night.

00:55:15.130 --> 00:55:19.070
AUDIENCE: So it's, kind
of, like a hired program,

00:55:19.070 --> 00:55:20.580
or is it parent
volunteers mostly?

00:55:20.580 --> 00:55:21.996
NADIA LOPEZ: It's
a hired program.

00:55:21.996 --> 00:55:24.020
We don't have parent volunteers.

00:55:24.020 --> 00:55:27.470
And oftentimes, it goes back
to parents' limitations,

00:55:27.470 --> 00:55:29.990
parents being comfortable,
and having something

00:55:29.990 --> 00:55:31.707
to contribute on that level.

00:55:31.707 --> 00:55:33.290
That's often at
times, but if a parent

00:55:33.290 --> 00:55:35.581
has something that they could
contribute, by all means,

00:55:35.581 --> 00:55:36.980
we accept them.

00:55:36.980 --> 00:55:39.815
But the reality is that we
don't have that in our building.

00:55:39.815 --> 00:55:41.210
AUDIENCE: No, it's fantastic
that you can do it.

00:55:41.210 --> 00:55:41.810
Thank you.

00:55:41.810 --> 00:55:43.640
NADIA LOPEZ: Thank you.

00:55:43.640 --> 00:55:45.452
Anyone else?

00:55:45.452 --> 00:55:46.910
AUDIENCE: I know
we're wrapping up,

00:55:46.910 --> 00:55:49.190
but just to leave us with
what we can do-- what can we

00:55:49.190 --> 00:55:51.280
all do from Google to help?

00:55:51.280 --> 00:55:54.080
NADIA LOPEZ: So that's
always a great question.

00:55:54.080 --> 00:55:55.850
A couple of things--

00:55:55.850 --> 00:56:00.360
I always open my doors and
say, my kids need to see you.

00:56:00.360 --> 00:56:03.090
They need to be able to see
individuals like yourselves

00:56:03.090 --> 00:56:06.060
and what you're doing,
so that they can see

00:56:06.060 --> 00:56:07.680
what their possibilities are.

00:56:07.680 --> 00:56:08.240
That's one.

00:56:08.240 --> 00:56:10.290
Two-- there are often
times when I have

00:56:10.290 --> 00:56:11.650
no idea what Google can offer.

00:56:11.650 --> 00:56:12.150
Right?

00:56:12.150 --> 00:56:13.830
It's the superficial
things that I see.

00:56:13.830 --> 00:56:15.300
I see that we can Google things.

00:56:15.300 --> 00:56:16.290
I see Google Hangouts.

00:56:16.290 --> 00:56:17.690
I see Google Docs.

00:56:17.690 --> 00:56:18.960
I understand Scratch.

00:56:18.960 --> 00:56:21.600
But there are other things
that Google can offer

00:56:21.600 --> 00:56:24.780
that I have no idea exists.

00:56:24.780 --> 00:56:29.850
So part of it is, educate
me on what that is.

00:56:29.850 --> 00:56:35.070
My overall goal is,
one day, in a way,

00:56:35.070 --> 00:56:38.670
to create more schools and
environments like this--

00:56:38.670 --> 00:56:40.410
to have those
Google-type schools,

00:56:40.410 --> 00:56:42.510
where it's about
true collaborations

00:56:42.510 --> 00:56:44.670
and setting up a
space that doesn't

00:56:44.670 --> 00:56:48.210
have as many constraints
as I have, because

00:56:48.210 --> 00:56:49.184
of the co-sharing.

00:56:49.184 --> 00:56:50.850
And really getting
people to understand,

00:56:50.850 --> 00:56:53.190
if you partner with
organizations like Google,

00:56:53.190 --> 00:56:55.800
Google is really willing to
take that on, and saying,

00:56:55.800 --> 00:56:58.500
we really want to be
invested in education.

00:56:58.500 --> 00:57:01.272
Let's create the spaces
that we do for the adults.

00:57:01.272 --> 00:57:03.480
But it makes no sense for
you to do it for the adults

00:57:03.480 --> 00:57:05.271
if you're not doing it
for the children who

00:57:05.271 --> 00:57:07.950
need to grow up to become those
adults to appreciate the space.

00:57:07.950 --> 00:57:10.122
Does that make sense?

00:57:10.122 --> 00:57:10.930
OK.

00:57:10.930 --> 00:57:12.630
So this was wonderful.

00:57:12.630 --> 00:57:14.800
I truly appreciate your time.

00:57:14.800 --> 00:57:16.530
I know some of you
have lunch or you have

00:57:16.530 --> 00:57:19.020
projects you need to work on.

00:57:19.020 --> 00:57:22.560
My story-- the full-out story
of how I opened up the school

00:57:22.560 --> 00:57:27.270
and a lot of the things that I
went through personally to get

00:57:27.270 --> 00:57:28.700
it to open--

00:57:28.700 --> 00:57:30.402
and it wasn't easy.

00:57:30.402 --> 00:57:32.610
It's, kind of, like, the
schools that I was in before

00:57:32.610 --> 00:57:37.670
was, dangerous minds means
lean on me, literally.

00:57:37.670 --> 00:57:41.160
However, had I not gone
through those experiences,

00:57:41.160 --> 00:57:43.350
I would not be as
relentless about creating

00:57:43.350 --> 00:57:47.520
a space where children are
safe, happy, learning to be--

00:57:47.520 --> 00:57:50.610
not just tolerant, because
we can tolerate a lot,

00:57:50.610 --> 00:57:53.040
but have to be accepting
of every single individual,

00:57:53.040 --> 00:57:55.570
because that's what
humanity is about.

00:57:55.570 --> 00:57:58.320
And so if I could do it
in Brownsville, Brooklyn

00:57:58.320 --> 00:58:00.480
under the circumstances
that I laid out,

00:58:00.480 --> 00:58:02.640
it can be done
anywhere in this world.

00:58:02.640 --> 00:58:04.050
Trust and believe that.

00:58:04.050 --> 00:58:07.350
So the story's in the
back for sale, yes.

00:58:07.350 --> 00:58:09.979
If anybody purchases it, I'll
be more than happy to sign it.

00:58:09.979 --> 00:58:11.520
But again, I thank
you, and thank you

00:58:11.520 --> 00:58:13.050
for this forum here at Google.

00:58:13.050 --> 00:58:16.100
[APPLAUSE]

